        // ── Units of Measure & Conversions (Article) ─────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Units of Measure & Conversions",
            Slug = "inventory-uom",
            Summary = "Manage the units a part can be counted, stocked, and bought in — and the conversion factors between them — from the Inventory Units of Measure tab.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 7,
            AppRoutes = """["/inventory/uom"]""",
            Tags = """["inventory","uom","units","conversions"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Units of Measure & Conversions\n\nA unit of measure (UOM) is how a part is counted — Each, Foot, Pound, Liter, and so on. The **Units of Measure** tab in Inventory (the rightmost tab, at `/inventory/uom`) is where you define the catalog of units your shop uses and the conversion factors between them, so a part bought by the box can still be stocked and consumed by the each.\n\nThe tab has two sections, switched by the buttons at the top: **Units of Measure** and **Conversions**.\n\n### Units of Measure\n\nThe Units of Measure list shows every unit with its code, name, symbol, category, decimal places, and a checkmark on the base unit for its category. Click **New UOM** to add one, or click any row to edit it.\n\nThe UOM dialog has these fields:\n\n- **Code** (required, up to 10 characters) — the short identifier, e.g. `EA`, `FT`, `LB`, `KG`. This is what appears compactly in tables and on documents.\n- **Name** (required, up to 50 characters) — the full name, e.g. `Each`, `Foot`, `Pound`, `Kilogram`.\n- **Category** (required) — the dimension the unit measures: **Count, Length, Weight, Volume, Area, or Time**. Conversions only make sense within a single category — you can convert feet to inches (both Length), but not pounds to feet.\n- **Symbol** (optional) — the display symbol, e.g. `ft`, `lb`, `kg`.\n- **Decimal Places** (required, 0–6) — how many decimals this unit allows. Set `0` for things counted in whole units (Each), and a higher value for measured quantities (e.g. `3` for kilograms).\n- **Sort Order** (optional) — controls where the unit appears in pick lists.\n- **Base Unit for Category** (toggle) — marks this unit as the reference unit that other units in the same category convert against. For Length you might make Inch (or Millimeter) the base; for Weight, Gram or Pound. The base unit is the anchor all conversions in that category pivot through.\n\n### Conversions\n\nSwitch to the **Conversions** section to define how one unit relates to another. The list shows From, To, the conversion factor, and whether the conversion is reversible. Click **New Conversion** to add one.\n\nThe Conversion dialog:\n\n- **From UOM** (required) — the unit you're converting *from*.\n- **To UOM** (required) — the unit you're converting *to*.\n- **Conversion Factor** (required, greater than zero) — how many *To* units equal one *From* unit. For example, `1 FT = 12 IN`, so From = FT, To = IN, Factor = `12`. The dialog's placeholder reminds you of this shape (`12 (1 ft = 12 in)`).\n- **Reversible (auto-creates inverse)** (toggle, on by default) — when enabled, saving `1 FT = 12 IN` also makes the system understand `1 IN = 1/12 FT` automatically, so you don't have to enter the inverse by hand. Leave it on unless you have a one-directional relationship.\n\n### Why this matters\n\nUOMs and their conversions let a part flow through your operation in whatever unit fits each step: you might **buy** wire by the spool, **stock** it by the foot, and **issue** it to a job by the inch. As long as the units share a category and a conversion exists between them, Forge keeps the math consistent — purchase quantities, on-hand balances, and job consumption all reconcile to the same physical material. Define the units once on this tab, and the rest of the system (Parts, Purchasing, Inventory) can speak them.\n\n### Tips\n\n- Pick **one base unit per category** and define every other unit in that category as a conversion to it — that keeps the conversion graph simple and avoids contradictory chains.\n- Set **Decimal Places** to match how the unit is really used. Counting in fractional eaches usually signals the wrong unit; a measured material like sheet metal area may need 2–3 decimals.\n- Keep **Reversible** on for normal physical units. The only time to turn it off is a genuinely one-way relationship.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Inventory — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "inventory-reference",
            Summary = "Edge-case and admin-config reference: single vs. multi-location gating, lot/serial fields and expiration highlighting, bin statuses and QC Hold/Release, Available-to-Promise, and movements-tab filtering.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/inventory"]""",
            Tags = """["inventory","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Inventory — Advanced Reference\n\nEdge-case and ancillary notes for the Inventory module. This is power-user / admin-config reference material, not a walkthrough — see the Overview, Guided Tour, and Field Reference for the everyday flows.\n\n## Single vs. Multi-Location (CAP-INV-MULTILOC)\n\nTwo distinct inventory shapes are gated by the `CAP-INV-MULTILOC` capability (default OFF):\n\n- **Single-location (capability OFF)** — on-hand is tracked as one pooled balance per part. The **Location** field is hidden in the Inventory Home verb dialogs; the server silently routes every Receive/Use/Count to the default location. Operators never have to think about bins.\n- **Multi-location (capability ON)** — inventory is tracked separately per location/plant, and inter-plant transfers become meaningful. The Location dropdown appears in the verb dialogs and stock-op dialogs so you can say exactly which bin stock entered or left. Required by multi-site shops.\n\nThe verb itself (Receive/Use/Count) is identical in both modes; only the optional location detail changes. The detailed Stock Ops **Transfer** dialog is where inter-location moves happen — it always writes a `Transfer` `BinMovement`.\n\n## Lot & Serial Fields, Expiration Highlighting\n\nThree traceability capabilities layer on top of core inventory:\n\n- **CAP-INV-LOTS** — lot-level traceability with expiry tracking and FEFO (First-Expired-First-Out) consumption order. For food, pharma, and chemicals where lot identity matters.\n- **CAP-INV-SERIALS** — per-unit serial-number tracking for high-value or regulated items; supports forward and backward trace.\n- Part-level intent is carried on `Part.TraceabilityType` (`None` / `Lot` / `Serial`), which replaced the legacy `IsSerialTracked` boolean.\n\nEach `BinContent` row carries these lot fields, surfaced in the expanded bin detail on the Stock tab:\n\n- **Lot Number** — your internal lot/batch identifier.\n- **Supplier Lot Number** — the vendor's lot number, kept distinct from your internal one.\n- **Lot Expiration Date** — drives the expiry highlight.\n\n**Expiration highlighting** is computed client-side from days-until-expiry: a lot already past its date renders with the `lot-expired` class; a lot within 30 days of expiry renders `lot-expiring-soon`. Lots with no expiration date are not highlighted.\n\n## Bin Content Statuses, QC Hold / Release\n\n`BinContentStatus` has exactly four values (wire form in parentheses): **Stored** (`Stored`), **Reserved** (`Reserved`), **Ready to Ship** (`ReadyToShip`), **QC Hold** (`QcHold`).\n\n- **Stored** — the default; available for picking, transfer, or reservation.\n- **Reserved** — held for a job or sales order; not pickable for other purposes until released.\n- **Ready to Ship** — staged for an outbound shipment.\n- **QC Hold** — awaiting quality inspection; cannot be picked or shipped.\n\n**QC Hold → Release cycle.** Incoming material that needs inspection is placed on QC Hold (commonly at receipt). It stays unpickable until it passes inspection, at which point a **QC Release** transition flips the status back to Stored and records a `BinMovement` with reason `QC Release`. This is the inventory-side hook for an inbound-inspection quality gate.\n\n## Available-to-Promise (ATP)\n\nATP answers \"can I actually promise this quantity, and by when?\" — it is supply-vs-demand math, not a raw on-hand lookup. It is gated by `CAP-PLAN-ATP` and exposed at `GET /api/v1/inventory/atp/{partId}?quantity=N` plus a time-phased `GET /api/v1/inventory/atp/{partId}/timeline?from=&to=`.\n\nThe `AtpResult` fields:\n\n- **onHand** — current physical on-hand.\n- **allocatedToOrders** — quantity already committed to orders (demand).\n- **scheduledReceipts** — quantity inbound on open POs (future supply).\n- **availableToPromise** — the net promisable quantity.\n- **earliestAvailableDate** — when the requested quantity can first be met (null if already coverable).\n- **canFulfill** — boolean: is the requested `quantity` promisable now.\n\nThe **timeline** endpoint returns `AtpBucket` rows (`date`, `cumulativeSupply`, `cumulativeDemand`, `netAvailable`) for a forward projection across the requested date window. Note ATP belongs to the planning capability family (`CAP-PLAN-*`), not the inventory family — it can be enabled or disabled independently of core inventory tracking.\n\n## Movements-Tab Filtering\n\nThe Movements log is a shared DataTable, so it inherits per-column sort and filtering. The **Reason** column filters against the `BinMovementReason` set: `Receive`, `Pick`, `Restock`, `QC Release`, `Ship`, `Move`, `Adjustment`, `Return`, `Transfer`, `Cycle Count`. Two of those reasons are system-generated rather than hand-picked: `Receive` (written when goods are received against a PO line) and `Cycle Count` (written when a count with variance is approved). On the Cycle Counts tab, the **Status** column is an enum filter (Pending / Approved / Rejected). Use these column filters to narrow a long audit trail to a single reason, status, date range, or operator before exporting.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Inventory training modules");
    }
